<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Cistanthe </i>species are deep-rooted perennials with rosettes of more or less fleshy leaves. The inflorescences sport tight clusters of flowers surrounded by conspicuous scarious bracts. Many references use the name <i>Calyptridium </i>(see Kelley et al. 2003). <i>Gayophytum </i>species and <i>Polygonum douglasii </i>are open, erect slender annuals often seen growing in rocky areas including along trails and other often-disturbed areas at upper-montane to alpine elevations. Other annual or perennial <i>Polygonum </i>species may be present. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance typically occurs in dry montane meadows adjacent to dense forests. Potter (2005) described stands as commonly occurring in upper-montane meadows adjacent to permanent streams or on upland convex slopes in the Sierra Nevada. Soils may be seasonally saturated from snowmelt and subsurface flow originating upslope, though they are dry by mid summer. Stands are inherently diverse and are analogous to the annual fields of the <i>Lasthenia californica-Plantago erecta-Vulpia microstachys </i>alliance at lower elevations in cismontane California. Many genera, including <i>Eriogonum, Gilia, Linanthus, Lotus, Madia, </i>and <i>Trifolium, </i>are common representatives of this functional group. We include the perennial <i>Astragalus bolanderi </i>association described by Potter (2005) in this alliance description because it occupies similar conditions and includes high constancy of <i>Cistanthe </i>and <i>Gayophytum </i>species. We expect further differentiation of this alliance to occur upon wider sampling of meadow settings throughout the mountains of the state. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
