    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of the species in this alliance includes the state’s mountains.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ad-e, Ag, Aj, Am-o, At). Stands occur at uppermontane elevations in dry and mesic meadows in the Marble Mountains (Stillman 1980), including at Haypress Meadows RNA with <i>Cistanthe umbellata</i> and <i>Gayophytum humile</i> (Imper 1988a, see Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). Stands occur on greywacke and shale on open ridges and slopes in the Yolla Bolly Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Keeler-Wolf 1974).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-e, Eh, Ej-k, Em, Eo, Eq, Et-u). Stands of the <i>Polygonum douglasii-Gayophytum diffusum</i> association exist in dry and mesic meadows at upper-montane to alpine elevations (Potter 2005). Stands of the <i>Astragalus bolanderi</i> with <i>C. umbellata</i> and <i>G. eriospermum</i> occur in dry subalpine meadows of the central and southern subsections (Potter 1998) and at Mount Pleasant RNA (Keeler-Wolf and Keeler-Wolf 1981, see Cheng 2004) in Plumas Co.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands provide general wildlife habitat value, species richness, and landscape level diversity in upper-montane habitats associated with <i>Abies magnifica </i>forests (Potter 1998). Many dry meadow locations containing this and related alliances are impacted by grazing and human-mediated impacts. Some species increase with increasing grazing (Potter 2005). Invasive non-native plants present include <i>Cirsium vulgare, Poa pratensis, Taraxacum officinale, </i>and <i>Verbascum thapsus</i>. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
